Raw dev notes -- The Unsung Heroes of Side Project Maintenance

Okay, so this past week or so has been a real grab bag of side project work. It's funny how you start these things with grand visions of new features, and then reality hits, and you spend most of your time on the unglamorous but absolutely essential stuff: bug fixes, infrastructure, and keeping the data fresh.

**What are these projects, anyway?**
I'm juggling a few things here. The "Synagogue Display System" is a little app I built to show various information (prayer times, announcements, etc.) in a local synagogue. "halachot-orvishua" is a content aggregator, pulling Q&A and articles from a specific religious law website to make it more accessible. The "RAG Knowledge Base Pipeline" is part of my ongoing experiments with AI and Retrieval-Augmented Generation – basically, building a personal, searchable knowledge base from various sources. And "smart-hebrew-rtl" is a utility for handling Hebrew text direction in specific contexts, which is always a fun challenge. They all exist because I either saw a direct need or wanted a sandbox to learn something new.

**What I actually did this past week:**
A lot of it was maintenance, honestly.

For the **Synagogue Display System**, I finally tackled some nagging issues. The biggest one was getting the logging right. It was dumping logs in weird places, which is a nightmare for debugging on a user's machine (even if that user is just me, sometimes!). So, I routed it properly to `%APPDATA%` and then had to wrestle with the installer to make sure it forced the app into the 64-bit Program Files directory, which is always a fun little dance with Windows installers. I also fixed a really specific bug where the `hebrew_day` was getting normalized in a way that broke a specific display requirement – had to `un-normalize` it, which sounds ridiculous but was necessary. And made sure alerts included a proper description, so they're actually useful.

On the **halachot-orvishua** and **RAG Knowledge Base Pipeline** fronts, it was mostly about keeping the data current. Just running the sync processes, pulling in a new Q&A for the halachot project, and a bunch of comment updates for the RAG KB. It's not glamorous, but it's crucial for these projects to stay relevant.

And for **smart-hebrew-rtl**, I cleaned up the packaging. Got dynamic versioning working (finally!), which means I don't have to manually update version numbers anymore, and ensured it always produces both necessary ZIP files for distribution. Small thing, but a quality-of-life improvement for future releases.

**What was hard or surprising:**
Honestly, the Windows installer stuff for the Synagogue Display System always gets me. It feels like black magic sometimes, trying to force it to do exactly what you want with paths and permissions. The `%APPDATA%` logging fix sounds simple, but getting it robustly implemented across the app and then making sure the installer doesn't mess it up is a multi-step headache.

The `un-normalize hebrew_day` bug was also a head-scratcher. It's a perfect example of how domain-specific requirements can clash with what seems like a "correct" or "normalized" data representation in code. You think you've got a clean data model, and then a real-world display need throws a wrench in it. It's a good reminder that "correct" is often contextual.

And while the sync commits look simple, the underlying systems for robustly checking for changes, handling diffs, and updating without breaking anything are surprisingly complex. It's easy to write a script that pulls data, much harder to write one that *only* pulls *new* data and handles updates gracefully.

**Personal reflection:**
This past week felt like a lot of "janitorial" work, to be honest. No flashy new features, just a lot of polishing, fixing, and making sure things run smoothly. It's not the most exciting part of development, but it's incredibly satisfying when you squash those annoying bugs or streamline a build process. It reinforces the idea that a project isn't just about the initial build; it's about ongoing care and feeding. I'm learning a lot about the less glamorous but utterly essential aspects of software lifecycle – deployment, user experience (even for myself!), and robust data management. It's a good lesson in patience and attention to detail.

**What's next:**
More of the same, probably. Keep chipping away at the backlog.
